<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is population density?", answer: "Population density is the number of people living per unit of land area, commonly expressed as people per square kilometer or people per square mile. It is a core metric in geography, demography, urban planning, and epidemiology because it captures how crowded a region is at a single glance, and it strongly influences infrastructure needs, housing demand, traffic, and disease transmission dynamics." },
  { question: "What counts as high population density?", answer: "There is no universal definition, but as a rough guide: under 10 people per square kilometer is very sparse (wilderness, rural interior); 10 to 100 is sparse and rural; 100 to 500 is moderate and suburban; 500 to 2,000 is urban; 2,000 to 10,000 is very dense inner city; and above 10,000 is hyperdense megacity core. Monaco, the densest sovereign country, has about 26,000 people per square kilometer. Manhattan averages around 27,000 per km², and Dhaka is even denser in spots." },
  { question: "Why is density more useful than raw population?", answer: "Total population tells you how many people live in a region, but not how they are distributed. Two cities with the same population can feel completely different if one is sprawled across a huge area and the other is packed into a small one. Density captures that distribution and is a better predictor of transit feasibility, energy demand per capita, land pricing, and disease spread than raw population alone." },
  { question: "How does area unit affect the result?", answer: "Density is population divided by area, so the unit of area determines the units of the answer. People per square kilometer is standard internationally; people per square mile is standard in the United States. Hectares and acres are useful for farms and small parcels. The calculator converts whichever unit you enter into km² and mi² automatically, so you can compare any region on equal footing." },
  { question: "What are some examples?", answer: "Mongolia has about 2 people per km² and is the least densely populated sovereign country. Australia has about 3 per km². The United States averages about 37 per km². Germany is 237 per km². Bangladesh is about 1,270 per km². City-states like Singapore (~8,400 per km²) and Monaco (~26,000 per km²) are the world's densest." }
]) %>

